name: Natalie_Claunch
title: Overwintering and cold tolerance in the Moor frog (Rana arvalis) across its range
notes_ID: The same animals were assesed for CTmin and LT50, hence the shared cohort_IDs
notes_sampling: Chernogolovka
notes_test: n_replicates_per_temp was different for each temperature. Frogs were placed in containers of 3-5 individuals, and some temperatures only have 5 or fewer individuals (Pop 1 ranges from 2-12 individuals, pop2 from 4-20 individuals, pop3 from 3-13 individuals). To determine # replicates I averaged # individuals per temp per population, divide by 5 (# individuals per cohort) and report this value. n was taken as the as n_test_temperatures * n_replicates_per_temp.
notes_UTL: Sample size unclear. LT50 was estimated based on survival rates at different temperatures.

name: Sarah Varon
title: Variao latitudinal nos limites de tolerncia e plasticidade trmica em anfbios em um cenrio de mudanas climticas: efeito dos micro-habitats, sazonalidade e filogenia
chapter_title: Latitudinal variation of thermal tolerance limits and vulnerability to extreme temperatures in amphibians: the effects of microhabitats, seasonality and phylogeny
notes_sampling: "tropical" community. Coordinates estimated based on Google Maps
notes_acclimation: Acclimated for 3-4 days
notes_test: Gosner stage was taken as the mean of the range reported
notes_UTL: Error not reported. Sample size was taken as 15 because authors state that they "analyzed a minimum of 15 individuals for all 60 species for each thermal tolerance limit". However, note that this may be an overestimate in some casesbecause they also state that "for some species we study a reduced sample because shortage of field collected tadpoles".

chapter_title: Latitudinal variation of thermal tolerance limits and vulnerability to extreme temperatures in amphibians: the effects of microhabitats, seasonality and phylogeny
notes_sampling: "tropical" community. Coordinates estimated based on Google Maps
notes_acclimation: Acclimated for 3-4 days
notes_test: Gosner stage was taken as the mean of the range reported
notes_UTL: Error not reported. Sample size was taken as 15 because authors state that they "analyzed a minimum of 15 individuals for all 60 species for each thermal tolerance limit". However, note that this may be an overestimate in some casesbecause they also state that "for some species we study a reduced sample because shortage of field collected tadpoles".

name: Rachel Oh
title: Divergence of thermal physiological traits in terrestrial breeding frogs along a tropical elevational gradient
notes_sampling: Geographical coordinates were not clearly reported. Only the location of some key Peruvian study sites were presented, but it was impossible to assign each site to a particular species. However, geographical coordinates are provided for the same species (and most likely for the same population in Rohr et al. 2018 (data from Catenazzi et al. 2014). The midpoint elevation was taken from Tab S3.
notes_acclimation: acclimation_time was taken as the mean of the range presented (2-3 days). Acclimation temperature was 16-21C so we taken the mean acclimation temperature and used SD_acclimation_temp was the variation around that mean
notes_UTL: The total sample size (196) was divided equally between the 14 species assessed

title: Physiological response and changes in swimming performance after thermal acclimation in juvenile chinese fire-belly newts, Cynops orientalis

name: Pietro Pollo
title: BALANCING HYPOXIA AND HYPOTHERMIA IN COLD-SUBMERGED FROGS
notes_ID: The same animals were tested at different time points, hence the shared cohort IDs
notes_sampling: Animals were "obtained from commercial suppliers (Blades Biological Co., UK), who collected the animals from natural populations in Ireland in the autumn of 1995". Coordinates were estimated from Google Maps.
notes_test: Normoxia (158 mmHg). Experiment lasted for 40h but figure with results only shows observations for 6h; sample size was 6 individuals but figure 1 shows number of total observations (in 6h), knowing there were 15 observations per hour, there were 540 (6*6*15) observations shown in figure 1; two treatments: normoxia (158mmHg) and hypoxia (25mmHg) but with the same individuals (started in normoxia [figure 1B] then were subjected to hypoxia [figure 1C]); individuals from figure 1A were actually in a constant temperature setting.
notes_UTL: Data was digitised from the figure, which only presented the % of observations. Therefore, standard error was based on a sample size of 100, but n_trait was taken as NA.

name: Pietro Pollo
title: BEHAVIORAL THERMOREGULATION BY BUFO AMERICANUS: THE IMPORTANCE OF THE HYDRIC ENVIRONMENT
notes_ID: The same animals were tested at different time points, hence the shared cohort IDs
notes_sampling: Animals were collected from permanent pond (Van Pond) near the University of Michigan Biological Station (UMBS) at Douglas Lake, Pellston, Michigan. Coordinates were estimated from Google Maps
notes_test: wet sand (soil water potential = 0kPa);  different groups depending on substrate: "(1) the sandy substratum of the gradient was saturated with water (soil water potential = 0 kPa); (2) sand in a portion of the gradient was dry (soil water potential < -1000 kPa), and a portion was saturated; and (3) all of the sand in the gradient was dry"; second treatment not extracted because there is preference for substrate and temperature at the same time (see figure 4); number of total observations should have been between 450 to 540 (5 groups * 6 individuals * 18-19 observations each), but that's not what I got from the histograms in figure 3 (I maintained the sample size from the figure extraction); figure 3b-f are from the same experiment but different "blocks" of observations (each with 10 min); body temperature was estimated from regressions that assessed the relationsip between substrate temperature and body temperature
